-- JOHN CHAPTER 20 — The Resurrection
-- 31 verses · Greek text · Word studies · Cross-refs
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 20,
  'John 20 is the resurrection chapter — the climax of the Gospel and the hinge of history. Four distinct encounters constitute the chapter: (1) the empty tomb discovered by Mary Magdalene, then Peter and the Beloved Disciple (vv.1-10); (2) Mary Magdalene''s encounter with the risen Jesus in the garden (vv.11-18) — the first resurrection appearance in John; (3) the appearance to the ten disciples on Easter evening (vv.19-23), including the giving of the Spirit and the commission to forgive and retain sins; (4) Thomas''s doubt and confession a week later (vv.24-29) — the great christological climax: ''My Lord and my God!'' The chapter closes with the first statement of the Gospel''s purpose (vv.30-31): ''these are written, that ye might believe that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of God; and that believing ye might have life through his name.'' John''s resurrection narrative is characterised by personal, intimate encounters — each person meets the risen Christ differently: Mary weeping by the tomb; the disciples behind locked doors; Thomas in his doubt. The risen Jesus addresses each person by name, in their specific need. The resurrection is not a theological abstraction but a personal encounter. The transformation of the disciples from hiding in fear to bold witnesses (Acts 2) is explicable only by the actual, bodily resurrection of Jesus Christ from the dead.',
  'I Have Seen the Lord — The Resurrection Appearances',
  'ἐγείρω (egeirō)',
  'To raise up, awaken, lift — used throughout the NT for resurrection. In the passive (ēgerthē — he was raised), it emphasises divine action: God the Father raised the Son from the dead (Romans 10:9; Galatians 1:1). In John, resurrection is also described as Jesus raising himself (10:17-18; 2:19: ''I will raise it up''). Both are true: the resurrection is the act of the triune God — the Father raises, the Son rises, the Spirit is the power of resurrection life (Romans 8:11). The perfect tense in the angel''s announcement (ēgerthē — ''he is risen'', Matthew 28:6) emphasises the abiding result: he was raised and remains risen. The risen life of Christ is permanent, glorified, unending (Romans 6:9: ''death hath no more dominion over him'').',
  '["The Empty Tomb (vv.1-10): The first day of the week cometh Mary Magdalene early when it was yet dark unto the sepulchre and seeth the stone taken away from the sepulchre. Then she runneth and cometh to Simon Peter and to the other disciple whom Jesus loved and saith unto them They have taken away the Lord out of the sepulchre and we know not where they have laid him. Peter therefore went forth and that other disciple and came to the sepulchre. So they ran both together and the other disciple did outrun Peter and came first to the sepulchre. And he stooping down and looking in saw the linen clothes lying yet went he not in. Then cometh Simon Peter following him and went into the sepulchre and seeth the linen clothes lie and the napkin that was about his head not lying with the linen clothes but wrapped together in a place by itself. Then went in also that other disciple which came first to the sepulchre and he saw and believed. For as yet they knew not the scripture that he must rise again from the dead. Then the disciples went away again unto their own home","The Appearance to Mary Magdalene (vv.11-18): But Mary stood without at the sepulchre weeping and as she wept she stooped down and looked into the sepulchre and seeth two angels in white sitting the one at the head and the other at the feet where the body of Jesus had lain. And they say unto her Woman why weepest thou? She saith unto them Because they have taken away my Lord and I know not where they have laid him. And when she had thus said she turned herself back and saw Jesus standing and knew not that it was Jesus. Jesus saith unto her Woman why weepest thou? whom seekest thou? She supposing him to be the gardener saith unto him Sir if thou have borne him hence tell me where thou hast laid him and I will take him away. Jesus saith unto her Mary. She turned herself and saith unto him Rabboni which is to say Master. Jesus saith unto her Touch me not for I am not yet ascended to my Father but go to my brethren and say unto them I ascend unto my Father and your Father and to my God and your God. Mary Magdalene came and told the disciples that she had seen the Lord and that he had spoken these things unto her","The Appearance to the Disciples (vv.19-23): Then the same day at evening being the first day of the week when the doors were shut where the disciples were assembled for fear of the Jews came Jesus and stood in the midst and saith unto them Peace be unto you. And when he had so said he shewed unto them his hands and his side. Then were the disciples glad when they saw the Lord. Then said Jesus to them again Peace be unto you as my Father hath sent me even so send I you. And when he had said this he breathed on them and saith unto them Receive ye the Holy Ghost. Whose soever sins ye remit they are remitted unto them and whose soever sins ye retain they are retained","Thomas''s Doubt and Confession (vv.24-29): But Thomas one of the twelve called Didymus was not with them when Jesus came. The other disciples therefore said unto him We have seen the Lord. But he said unto them Except I shall see in his hands the print of the nails and put my finger into the print of the nails and thrust my hand into his side I will not believe. And after eight days again his disciples were within and Thomas with them then came Jesus the doors being shut and stood in the midst and said Peace be unto you. Then saith he to Thomas Reach hither thy finger and behold my hands and reach hither thy hand and thrust it into my side and be not faithless but believing. And Thomas answered and said unto him My Lord and my God. Jesus saith unto him Thomas because thou hast seen me thou hast believed blessed are they that have not seen and yet have believed","The Purpose of the Gospel (vv.30-31): And many other signs truly did Jesus in the presence of his disciples which are not written in this book. But these are written that ye might believe that Jesus is the Christ the Son of God and that believing ye might have life through his name"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'John';

-- Step 2: Insert all 31 verses
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'The first day of the week cometh Mary Magdalene early, when it was yet dark, unto the sepulchre, and seeth the stone taken away from the sepulchre.',
   'Τῇ δὲ μιᾷ τῶν σαββάτων Μαρία ἡ Μαγδαληνὴ ἔρχεται πρωῒ σκοτίας ἔτι οὔσης εἰς τὸ μνημεῖον καὶ βλέπει τὸν λίθον ἠρμένον ἐκ τοῦ μνημείου',
   'Tē de mia tōn sabbatōn Maria hē Magdalēnē erchetai prōi skotias eti ousēs eis to mnēmeion kai blepei ton lithon ērmenon ek tou mnēmeiou',
   '''The first day of the week'' (tē mia tōn sabbatōn — on the first of the Sabbath-week). The resurrection occurs on the first day — Sunday. This is the beginning of the new creation: as God began creation on the first day (Genesis 1:3), the new creation begins on the first day with the resurrection of the Son of God. ''When it was yet dark'' (skotias eti ousēs — while it was still dark). Mary comes in the dark — John''s characteristic symbolism. She leaves in the dark; she will return and find the Light. ''The stone taken away'' (ton lithon ērmenon — the stone having been lifted away; perfect passive participle: removed and remains removed). Matthew 28:2 records the angel moving the stone; the stone is removed not to let Jesus out (the resurrection body can pass through walls, v.19) but to let the witnesses in.',
   NULL),
  (2, 'Then she runneth, and cometh to Simon Peter, and to the other disciple, whom Jesus loved, and saith unto them, They have taken away the Lord out of the sepulchre, and we know not where they have laid him.',
   'τρέχει οὖν καὶ ἔρχεται πρὸς Σίμωνα Πέτρον καὶ πρὸς τὸν ἄλλον μαθητὴν ὃν ἐφίλει ὁ Ἰησοῦς καὶ λέγει αὐτοῖς Ἦραν τὸν κύριον ἐκ τοῦ μνημείου καὶ οὐκ οἴδαμεν ποῦ ἔθηκαν αὐτόν',
   'trechei oun kai erchetai pros Simōna Petron kai pros ton allon mathētēn hon ephilei ho Iēsous kai legei autois Ēran ton kyrion ek tou mnēmeiou kai ouk oidamen pou ethēkan auton',
   '''They have taken away the Lord'' (Ēran ton kyrion — they have taken the Lord). Mary assumes grave-robbery. ''We know not'' (ouk oidamen — we do not know; the ''we'' suggests other women were present, cf. Luke 24:1,10: ''the other women''). Her grief is deep and her loss complete: she has lost him in death, and now even the body is gone. The pathos of Mary''s situation — love with no object, grief with no resolution — is the darkness before the dawn. She calls him ''the Lord'' (ton kyrion) — already the title of the risen Christ, though she does not yet know he is risen.',
   NULL),
  (3, 'Peter therefore went forth, and that other disciple, and came to the sepulchre.',
   'Ἐξῆλθεν οὖν ὁ Πέτρος καὶ ὁ ἄλλος μαθητής καὶ ἤρχοντο εἰς τὸ μνημεῖον',
   'Exēlthen oun ho Petros kai ho allos mathētēs kai ērchonto eis to mnēmeion',
   'The two disciples run to the tomb — Peter and the Beloved Disciple. The race to the tomb is described with vivid, personal detail that marks this as an eyewitness account. The narrative slows deliberately to attend to small but significant physical details: the linen clothes, the napkin, who went in first, what each one saw. These details have the feel of remembered experience.',
   NULL),
  (4, 'So they ran both together: and the other disciple did outrun Peter, and came first to the sepulchre.',
   'ἔτρεχον δὲ οἱ δύο ὁμοῦ καὶ ὁ ἄλλος μαθητὴς προέδραμεν τάχιον τοῦ Πέτρου καὶ ἦλθεν πρῶτος εἰς τὸ μνημεῖον',
   'etrechon de hoi dyo homou kai ho allos mathētēs proedrailen tachion tou Petrou kai ēlthen prōtos eis to mnēmeion',
   '''The other disciple did outrun Peter'' (proedrailen tachion tou Petrou — ran ahead faster than Peter). The detail of the race has charmed readers for centuries — the younger disciple (John) outrunning the older Peter. The Beloved Disciple arrives first but waits at the entrance; Peter arrives and goes straight in — character revealed in a footrace.',
   NULL),
  (5, 'And he stooping down, and looking in, saw the linen clothes lying; yet went he not in.',
   'καὶ παρακύψας βλέπει κείμενα τὰ ὀθόνια οὐ μέντοι εἰσῆλθεν',
   'kai parakypas blepei keimena ta othōnia ou mentoi eisēlthen',
   '''Stooping down, and looking in'' (parakypas — having stooped/bent down to look; parakyptō: to stoop and look). The tomb is cut into rock with a low entrance; one must stoop to enter. ''Saw the linen clothes lying'' (blepei keimena ta othōnia — sees the linen strips lying; blepō: a quick look, a casual seeing). The Beloved Disciple looks in and sees the grave clothes but hesitates to enter — whether from reverence, uncertainty, or waiting for Peter.',
   NULL),
  (6, 'Then cometh Simon Peter following him, and went into the sepulchre, and seeth the linen clothes lie,',
   'ἔρχεται οὖν Σίμων Πέτρος ἀκολουθῶν αὐτῷ καὶ εἰσῆλθεν εἰς τὸ μνημεῖον καὶ θεωρεῖ τὰ ὀθόνια κείμενα',
   'erchetai oun Simōn Petros akolouthōn autō kai eisēlthen eis to mnēmeion kai theōrei ta othōnia keimena',
   '''Seeth the linen clothes lie'' (theōrei ta othōnia keimena — beholds/observes the linen strips lying; theōreō: sustained, careful observation, more than a glance). Peter goes in and examines more carefully. The use of theōreō (sustained seeing) vs. blepō (quick seeing) in vv.5-6 is a linguistic distinction John makes deliberately: the Beloved Disciple glances; Peter studies.',
   NULL),
  (7, 'And the napkin, that was about his head, not lying with the linen clothes, but wrapped together in a place by itself.',
   'καὶ τὸ σουδάριον ὃ ἦν ἐπὶ τῆς κεφαλῆς αὐτοῦ οὐ μετὰ τῶν ὀθονίων κείμενον ἀλλὰ χωρὶς ἐντετυλιγμένον εἰς ἕνα τόπον',
   'kai to soudation ho ēn epi tēs kephalēs autou ou meta tōn othoniōn keimenon alla chōris entetyleimenon eis hena topon',
   '''The napkin... wrapped together in a place by itself'' (to soudation... entyleimenon eis hena topon — the face cloth... rolled up in one place by itself). ''Soudation'' (from Latin: sudarium — a sweat cloth, face cloth). The precise arrangement is significant: grave-robbers would not fold the grave clothes; they would take the body with them. The ordered arrangement of the linen — body clothes lying flat (as if the body simply passed through them), face cloth separately rolled — speaks of deliberate, unhurried departure. This is the evidence that struck the Beloved Disciple (v.8).',
   NULL),
  (8, 'Then went in also that other disciple, which came first to the sepulchre, and he saw, and believed.',
   'τότε οὖν εἰσῆλθεν καὶ ὁ ἄλλος μαθητὴς ὁ ἐλθὼν πρῶτος εἰς τὸ μνημεῖον καὶ εἶδεν καὶ ἐπίστευσεν',
   'tote oun eisēlthen kai ho allos mathētēs ho elthōn prōtos eis to mnēmeion kai eiden kai episteusen',
   '''He saw, and believed'' (eiden kai episteusen — he saw and believed). The third verb for seeing in this passage: eiden (from horaō — the deepest, most penetrating form of seeing, insight). ''He saw'' — with full perception of the evidence — ''and believed'' — the first Easter faith, based on the physical evidence of the empty tomb and the folded grave clothes. He does not yet have the full understanding (v.9) but responds to the evidence with faith.',
   NULL),
  (9, 'For as yet they knew not the scripture, that he must rise again from the dead.',
   'οὐδέπω γὰρ ᾔδεισαν τὴν γραφὴν ὅτι δεῖ αὐτὸν ἐκ νεκρῶν ἀναστῆναι',
   'oudepō gar ēdeisan tēn graphēn hoti dei auton ek nekrōn anastēnai',
   '''They knew not the scripture, that he must rise again'' (oudepō gar ēdeisan tēn graphēn — for as yet they had not known the scripture). The disciples had not yet connected the resurrection prophecies (Psalm 16:10; Isaiah 53:10-12; Jonah; Hosea 6:2) to Jesus. Understanding comes later, through the Spirit (16:13; Luke 24:45-46). The Beloved Disciple believed on the basis of what he saw; full scriptural understanding would follow. Faith can precede full theological articulation.',
   NULL),
  (10, 'Then the disciples went away again unto their own home.',
   'ἀπῆλθον οὖν πάλιν πρὸς αὑτοὺς οἱ μαθηταί',
   'apēlthon oun palin pros hautous hoi mathētai',
   'The two disciples leave. They have seen the evidence; one has believed. But they leave without encountering the risen Jesus — that privilege falls first to Mary. The disciples'' departure leaves Mary alone at the tomb, still weeping — setting the stage for the most tender resurrection encounter in any of the Gospels.',
   NULL),
  (11, 'But Mary stood without at the sepulchre weeping: and as she wept, she stooped down, and looked into the sepulchre,',
   'Μαρία δὲ εἱστήκει πρὸς τῷ μνημείῳ κλαίουσα ἔξω ὡς οὖν ἔκλαιεν παρέκυψεν εἰς τὸ μνημεῖον',
   'Maria de heistēkei pros tō mnēmeiō klaiousa exō hōs oun eklaien parekypsen eis to mnēmeion',
   '''Mary stood without at the sepulchre weeping'' (Maria de heistēkei pros tō mnēmeiō klaiousa exō — Mary was standing outside at the tomb, weeping). ''Klaiousa'' (weeping; klaiō: to weep, wail; a word for audible weeping/crying). Mary''s love is expressed in persistence: the disciples have gone home, but she remains. Her devotion outlasts the others'' curiosity. It is love that keeps her at the empty tomb in the dark.',
   NULL),
  (12, 'And seeth two angels in white sitting, the one at the head, and the other at the feet, where the body of Jesus had lain.',
   'καὶ θεωρεῖ δύο ἀγγέλους ἐν λευκοῖς καθεζομένους ἕνα πρὸς τῇ κεφαλῇ καὶ ἕνα πρὸς τοῖς ποσίν ὅπου ἔκειτο τὸ σῶμα τοῦ Ἰησοῦ',
   'kai theōrei dyo anggelous en leukois kathezomenous hena pros tē kephalē kai hena pros tois posin hopou ekeito to sōma tou Iēsou',
   '''Two angels in white'' (dyo anggelous en leukois — two angels in white). In John, only Mary sees the angels; the disciples presumably departed before the angel appearances. The two angels, one at the head and one at the feet — where the body had lain — recall the two cherubim on the ark of the covenant (Exodus 25:18-22), between which God''s presence dwelled. The empty space between the angels is the mercy seat — the place where atonement is made, now empty because the sacrifice is complete.',
   NULL),
  (13, 'And they say unto her, Woman, why weepest thou? She saith unto them, Because they have taken away my Lord, and I know not where they have laid him.',
   'καὶ λέγουσιν αὐτῇ ἐκεῖνοι Γύναι τί κλαίεις λέγει αὐτοῖς Ὅτι ἦραν τὸν κύριόν μου καὶ οὐκ οἶδα ποῦ ἔθηκαν αὐτόν',
   'kai legousin autē ekeinoi Gynai ti klaieis legei autois Hoti ēran ton kyrion mou kai ouk oida pou ethēkan auton',
   '''They have taken away my Lord'' (ēran ton kyrion mou — they have taken my Lord; the personal possessive: ''my Lord''). Even the sight of two angelic beings in a sealed tomb does not distract Mary from her grief — she wants the body of Jesus. Her love is so fixed on him that nothing can redirect it. ''Kyrios'' (Lord) — the word that will become the central confession of the resurrection church (1 Corinthians 12:3; Romans 10:9; Philippians 2:11).',
   NULL),
  (14, 'And when she had thus said, she turned herself back, and saw Jesus standing, and knew not that it was Jesus.',
   'καὶ ταῦτα εἰποῦσα ἐστράφη εἰς τὰ ὀπίσω καὶ θεωρεῖ τὸν Ἰησοῦν ἑστῶτα καὶ οὐκ ᾔδει ὅτι Ἰησοῦς ἐστιν',
   'kai tauta eipousa estraphē eis ta opisō kai theōrei ton Iēsoun hestōta kai ouk ēdei hoti Iēsous estin',
   '''She turned herself back, and saw Jesus standing, and knew not that it was Jesus'' (ouk ēdei hoti Iēsous estin — she did not know that it was Jesus). The risen Christ is not immediately recognisable — a pattern consistent across all the resurrection appearances (Luke 24:16; John 21:4; Mark 16:12). The resurrection body is a glorified body — continuous with but transformed from the pre-death body (1 Corinthians 15:42-44). Mary does not recognise him initially, perhaps because her eyes are blurred with tears, or because the resurrection form is different.',
   NULL),
  (15, 'Jesus saith unto her, Woman, why weepest thou? whom seekest thou? She, supposing him to be the gardener, saith unto him, Sir, if thou have borne him hence, tell me where thou hast laid him, and I will take him away.',
   'λέγει αὐτῇ Ἰησοῦς Γύναι τί κλαίεις τίνα ζητεῖς ἐκείνη δοκοῦσα ὅτι ὁ κηπουρός ἐστιν λέγει αὐτῷ Κύριε εἰ σύ ἐβάστασας αὐτόν εἰπέ μοι ποῦ ἔθηκας αὐτόν κἀγὼ αὐτὸν ἀρῶ',
   'legei autē Iēsous Gynai ti klaieis tina zēteis ekeinē dokousa hoti ho kēpouros estin legei autō Kyrie ei sy ebastasas auton eipe moi pou ethēkas auton kagō auton arō',
   '''Whom seekest thou?'' (tina zēteis — whom are you seeking?). The first question Jesus ever asked in this Gospel was ''What seek ye?'' (1:38). Now, after his death and resurrection, he asks the seeking question again — but personalised: not ''what'' but ''whom.'' Mary supposed him to be ''the gardener'' (ho kēpouros) — an understandable mistake: who else would be in a garden at dawn? The irony: Adam was the first gardener (Genesis 2:15), and Adam''s fall brought death. The Second Adam, the true Gardener, restores life in a garden.',
   NULL),
  (16, 'Jesus saith unto her, Mary. She turned herself, and saith unto him, Rabboni; which is to say, Master.',
   'λέγει αὐτῇ Ἰησοῦς Μαριάμ στραφεῖσα ἐκείνη λέγει αὐτῷ Ἑβραϊστί Ῥαββουνί ὃ λέγεται Διδάσκαλε',
   'legei autē Iēsous Mariam strapheisa ekeinē legei autō Hebraisti Rabboyni ho legetai Didaskale',
   '''Mary'' (Mariam — her Aramaic name). One word. Her name spoken by the risen Lord. Jesus said in 10:3: ''he calleth his own sheep by name.'' This is that moment: the Good Shepherd calls the sheep by name, and she recognises the voice instantly. ''Rabboni'' (Hebraisti Rabbouni — in Hebrew/Aramaic, Rabboni; a heightened form of Rabbi: ''my great master/teacher''). The one word from Jesus produces instant recognition; the recognition produces the Aramaic title of deepest personal devotion. The resurrection is not a theological idea but a personal encounter.',
   NULL),
  (17, 'Jesus saith unto her, Touch me not; for I am not yet ascended to my Father: but go to my brethren, and say unto them, I ascend unto my Father, and your Father; and to my God, and your God.',
   'λέγει αὐτῇ Ἰησοῦς Μή μου ἅπτου οὔπω γὰρ ἀναβέβηκα πρὸς τὸν πατέρα πορεύου δὲ πρὸς τοὺς ἀδελφούς μου καὶ εἰπὲ αὐτοῖς Ἀναβαίνω πρὸς τὸν πατέρα μου καὶ πατέρα ὑμῶν καὶ θεόν μου καὶ θεὸν ὑμῶν',
   'legei autē Iēsous Mē mou haptou oupō gar anabebēka pros ton patera poreuou de pros tous adelphous mou kai eipe autois Anabainō pros ton patera mou kai patera hymōn kai theon mou kai theon hymōn',
   '''Touch me not; for I am not yet ascended'' (Mē mou haptou — Do not touch/cling to me; present imperative with mē: stop touching, or do not keep touching). The Latin Noli me tangere. The precise meaning is debated: is it a prohibition of all touch (impossible, since he invites Thomas to touch him v.27)? Or a prohibition of clinging/detaining him? The latter is more likely: Mary must not try to keep the risen Jesus in the resurrection form; his destination is the ascension, and she must not delay his departure by clinging. The commission replaces the clinging. ''My Father and your Father; my God and your God'' — a careful, precise formulation: the relationship is analogous but not identical. He is Son by nature; they are sons and daughters by adoption (Romans 8:15-17). Both relationships are with the same God.',
   NULL),
  (18, 'Mary Magdalene came and told the disciples that she had seen the Lord, and that he had spoken these things unto her.',
   'ἔρχεται Μαρία ἡ Μαγδαληνὴ ἀγγέλλουσα τοῖς μαθηταῖς ὅτι ἑώρακα τὸν κύριον καὶ ταῦτα εἶπεν αὐτῇ',
   'erchetai Maria hē Magdalēnē angellousa tois mathētais hoti heōraka ton kyrion kai tauta eipen autē',
   '''I have seen the Lord'' (heōraka ton kyrion — I have seen the Lord; perfect: I have seen and the seeing stands). Mary is the first apostle of the resurrection — the first human being to proclaim the risen Christ. ''Apostle'' means ''one sent''; Jesus sent (v.17) her to the disciples with the resurrection message. The church''s tradition has rightly called her ''apostola apostolorum'' (apostle to the apostles). Her testimony is rejected by the disciples (Luke 24:11: ''their words seemed to them as idle tales'') — but it is true.',
   NULL),
  (19, 'Then the same day at evening, being the first day of the week, when the doors were shut where the disciples were assembled for fear of the Jews, came Jesus and stood in the midst, and saith unto them, Peace be unto you.',
   'Οὔσης οὖν ὀψίας τῇ ἡμέρᾳ ἐκείνῃ τῇ μιᾷ σαββάτων καὶ τῶν θυρῶν κεκλεισμένων ὅπου ἦσαν οἱ μαθηταὶ διὰ τὸν φόβον τῶν Ἰουδαίων ἦλθεν ὁ Ἰησοῦς καὶ ἔστη εἰς τὸ μέσον καὶ λέγει αὐτοῖς Εἰρήνη ὑμῖν',
   'Ousēs oun opsias tē hēmera ekeinē tē mia sabbatōn kai tōn thurōn kekleismenōn hopou ēsan hoi mathētai dia ton phobon tōn Ioudaiōn ēlthen ho Iēsous kai estē eis to meson kai legei autois Eirēnē hymin',
   '''The doors were shut... came Jesus and stood in the midst'' (tōn thurōn kekleismenōn... ēlthen ho Iēsous kai estē eis to meson — the doors having been locked... Jesus came and stood in the midst). The locked doors do not hinder the risen body of Christ. The resurrection body is not a ghost (Luke 24:39-43: he eats; 24:39: ''Handle me and see; for a spirit hath not flesh and bones'') but it is not bound by the physical limitations of the pre-resurrection body. ''Peace be unto you'' (Eirēnē hymin — Peace to you) — the standard Hebrew greeting ''Shalom'' but transformed: this is the peace promised in 14:27, now delivered in the presence of the risen Christ.',
   NULL),
  (20, 'And when he had so said, he shewed unto them his hands and his side. Then were the disciples glad, when they saw the Lord.',
   'καὶ τοῦτο εἰπὼν ἔδειξεν τὰς χεῖρας καὶ τὴν πλευρὰν αὐτοῖς ἐχάρησαν οὖν οἱ μαθηταὶ ἰδόντες τὸν κύριον',
   'kai touto eipōn edeixen tas cheiras kai tēn pleuran autois echarēsan oun hoi mathētai idontes ton kyrion',
   '''He shewed unto them his hands and his side'' (edeixen tas cheiras kai tēn pleuran autois — he showed them his hands and his side). The wounds of the crucifixion remain in the resurrection body — the nail prints, the spear wound. This is theologically significant: the risen Christ carries the marks of the cross into eternity. Revelation 5:6 describes the Lamb ''as it had been slain'' in the heavenly throne room. The resurrection does not erase the cross but glorifies it. ''The disciples were glad'' (echarēsan — they rejoiced; the fulfilment of 16:20-22).',
   NULL),
  (21, 'Then said Jesus to them again, Peace be unto you: as my Father hath sent me, even so send I you.',
   'εἶπεν οὖν αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς πάλιν Εἰρήνη ὑμῖν καθὼς ἀπέσταλκέν με ὁ πατήρ κἀγὼ πέμπω ὑμᾶς',
   'eipen oun autois ho Iēsous palin Eirēnē hymin kathōs apestalken me ho patēr kagō pempō hymas',
   '''As my Father hath sent me, even so send I you'' (kathōs apestalken me ho patēr, kagō pempō hymas — just as the Father has sent me, so I also send you). The Great Commission in John: the disciples'' mission is modelled on and grounded in the Son''s mission from the Father (17:18). ''Apestalken'' (perfect: has sent and the sending stands) vs. ''pempō'' (present: I am sending now). Both verbs for ''send'' are used — apostello and pempō — the full authority of divine commission.',
   NULL),
  (22, 'And when he had said this, he breathed on them, and saith unto them, Receive ye the Holy Ghost:',
   'καὶ τοῦτο εἰπὼν ἐνεφύσησεν καὶ λέγει αὐτοῖς Λάβετε πνεῦμα ἅγιον',
   'kai touto eipōn enephysēsen kai legei autois Labete pneuma hagion',
   '''He breathed on them'' (enephysēsen — he breathed into/upon them; emphysao: to breathe into; only here in the NT). The same verb used in Genesis 2:7 (LXX: enephysēsen — God breathed into Adam''s nostrils the breath of life). The new creation corresponds to the first creation: as God breathed life into Adam, the risen Son breathes the life of the Spirit into the new humanity. ''Receive ye the Holy Ghost'' (Labete pneuma hagion — receive Holy Spirit; without the article: receive [a gift of] Holy Spirit). This is a preliminary, anticipatory gift of the Spirit — a foretaste of Pentecost (Acts 2). The relationship between this gift and Pentecost is debated; most scholars see this as an earnest or a symbolic act of promise.',
   NULL),
  (23, 'Whose soever sins ye remit, they are remitted unto them; and whose soever sins ye retain, they are retained.',
   'ἄν τινων ἀφῆτε τὰς ἁμαρτίας ἀφίενται αὐτοῖς ἄν τινων κρατῆτε κεκράτηνται',
   'an tinōn aphēte tas hamartias aphientai autois an tinōn kratēte kekratēntai',
   '''Whose soever sins ye remit, they are remitted; whose soever sins ye retain, they are retained'' — the power of the keys (Matthew 16:19; 18:18). This is the apostolic authority to proclaim forgiveness and judgment in accordance with the gospel. It is not an independent priestly authority to forgive sin (only God forgives sin, Mark 2:7) but the authoritative declaration of the gospel: those who believe the apostolic message of forgiveness receive forgiveness; those who reject it retain their sins. The church''s mission is proclamation, and that proclamation has binding consequences.',
   NULL),
  (24, 'But Thomas, one of the twelve, called Didymus, was not with them when Jesus came.',
   'Θωμᾶς δὲ εἷς ἐκ τῶν δώδεκα ὁ λεγόμενος Δίδυμος οὐκ ἦν μετ᾽ αὐτῶν ὅτε ἦλθεν Ἰησοῦς',
   'Thōmas de heis ek tōn dōdeka ho legomenos Didymos ouk ēn met autōn hote ēlthen Iēsous',
   '''Thomas... was not with them'' (ouk ēn met autōn — was not with them). Thomas''s absence on Easter evening is not explained. Perhaps he was too grief-stricken to join the others; perhaps the meeting was held so privately he was not found. His absence means he misses the first appearance and must receive the testimony of the others secondhand. When people are absent from the community of faith, they miss what only that community can give.',
   NULL),
  (25, 'The other disciples therefore said unto him, We have seen the Lord. But he said unto them, Except I shall see in his hands the print of the nails, and put my finger into the print of the nails, and thrust my hand into his side, I will not believe.',
   'ἔλεγον οὖν αὐτῷ οἱ ἄλλοι μαθηταί Ἑωράκαμεν τὸν κύριον ὁ δὲ εἶπεν αὐτοῖς Ἐὰν μὴ ἴδω ἐν ταῖς χερσὶν αὐτοῦ τὸν τύπον τῶν ἥλων καὶ βάλω τὸν δάκτυλόν μου εἰς τὸν τύπον τῶν ἥλων καὶ βάλω μου τὴν χεῖρα εἰς τὴν πλευρὰν αὐτοῦ οὐ μὴ πιστεύσω',
   'elegon oun autō hoi alloi mathētai Heōrakamen ton kyrion ho de eipen autois Ean mē idō en tais chersin autou ton typon tōn hēlōn kai balō ton daktylo mou eis ton typon tōn hēlōn kai balō mou tēn cheira eis tēn pleuran autou ou mē pisteusō',
   '''Except I shall see... I will not believe'' (Ean mē idō... ou mē pisteusō — unless I see... I will certainly not believe). Thomas demands empirical verification of the most specific kind: the wound-marks of the nails and the spear. His demand is remarkably precise — he specifies exactly what he needs. He refuses to believe on the testimony of the others. This is not unreasonable (the resurrection is the most extraordinary claim in history) but it is inadequate: the risen Christ is not a body to be empirically verified but a Lord to be personally encountered.',
   NULL),
  (26, 'And after eight days again his disciples were within, and Thomas with them: then came Jesus, the doors being shut, and stood in the midst, and said, Peace be unto you.',
   'καὶ μεθ᾽ ἡμέρας ὀκτὼ πάλιν ἦσαν ἔσω οἱ μαθηταὶ αὐτοῦ καὶ Θωμᾶς μετ᾽ αὐτῶν ἔρχεται ὁ Ἰησοῦς τῶν θυρῶν κεκλεισμένων καὶ ἔστη εἰς τὸ μέσον καὶ εἶπεν Εἰρήνη ὑμῖν',
   'kai meth hēmeras oktō palin ēsan esō hoi mathētai autou kai Thōmas met autōn erchetai ho Iēsous tōn thurōn kekleismenōn kai estē eis to meson kai eipen Eirēnē hymin',
   '''After eight days'' (meth hēmeras oktō — after eight days; the following Sunday). Jesus returns specifically for Thomas. His patience with the doubter is pastoral: he does not rebuke Thomas''s absence, does not shame his demand, but meets him exactly where he is. Eight days — the eighth day is the day of new creation (circumcision on the eighth day; the octave of Easter; Sunday as the new Sabbath/eighth day). The assembly of disciples on the first/eighth day anticipates the pattern of Christian Sunday worship.',
   NULL),
  (27, 'Then saith he to Thomas, Reach hither thy finger, and behold my hands; and reach hither thy hand, and thrust it into my side: and be not faithless, but believing.',
   'εἶτα λέγει τῷ Θωμᾷ Φέρε τὸν δάκτυλόν σου ὧδε καὶ ἴδε τὰς χεῖράς μου καὶ φέρε τὴν χεῖρά σου καὶ βάλε εἰς τὴν πλευράν μου καὶ μὴ γίνου ἄπιστος ἀλλὰ πιστός',
   'eita legei tō Thōma Phere ton daktylo sou hōde kai ide tas cheiras mou kai phere tēn cheira sou kai bale eis tēn pleuran mou kai mē ginou apistos alla pistos',
   '''Jesus knew Thomas''s exact words (v.25) and addresses them precisely — ''reach thy finger... thrust it into my side'' — the identical language Thomas used in his demand. Jesus was absent from the room when Thomas spoke; he heard across time and space. He comes for Thomas with perfect knowledge of his doubt and perfect love for his person. ''Be not faithless, but believing'' (mē ginou apistos alla pistos — do not become faithless but faithful/believing). The call is not to blind credulity but to the willing trust that responds to evidence.',
   NULL),
  (28, 'And Thomas answered and said unto him, My Lord and my God.',
   'ἀπεκρίθη Θωμᾶς καὶ εἶπεν αὐτῷ Ὁ κύριός μου καὶ ὁ θεός μου',
   'apekrithē Thōmas kai eipen autō Ho kyrios mou kai ho theos mou',
   '''My Lord and my God'' (Ho kyrios mou kai ho theos mou). The christological climax of the Fourth Gospel. Thomas''s confession is the highest in any of the Gospels: ''Lord'' (kyrios — a title of the risen Christ, the Greek equivalent of Adonai) and ''God'' (theos — God, the divine name). The confession is explicitly addressed to Jesus (''to him''). This is not an exclamation of surprise but a confession of faith. Thomas had demanded empirical proof; the encounter with the risen Christ produces something beyond empirical certainty — personal surrender: ''MY Lord and MY God'' (the possessives are emphatic). This verse is one of the clearest affirmations of Christ''s full deity in the NT (cf. 1:1,18; Romans 9:5; Titus 2:13; Hebrews 1:8; 2 Peter 1:1; 1 John 5:20).',
   NULL),
  (29, 'Jesus saith unto him, Thomas, because thou hast seen me, thou hast believed: blessed are they that have not seen, and yet have believed.',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ ὁ Ἰησοῦς ὅτι ἑώρακάς με πεπίστευκας μακάριοι οἱ μὴ ἰδόντες καὶ πιστεύσαντες',
   'legei autō ho Iēsous hoti heōrakas me pepistekas makarioi hoi mē idontes kai pisteusantes',
   '''Blessed are they that have not seen, and yet have believed'' (makarioi hoi mē idontes kai pisteusantes — blessed are those not having seen and yet having believed). A beatitude for all post-resurrection believers. Thomas was blessed to see and believe; those who will come to faith without eyewitness encounter with the risen Christ are equally — perhaps specially — blessed. This verse is John''s pastoral bridge between the Gospel narrative and the reader: ''you have not seen, but you can believe, and believing you will have life'' (v.31). The entire purpose of the Gospel is to enable this non-eyewitness faith.',
   NULL),
  (30, 'And many other signs truly did Jesus in the presence of his disciples, which are not written in this book:',
   'Πολλὰ μὲν οὖν καὶ ἄλλα σημεῖα ἐποίησεν ὁ Ἰησοῦς ἐνώπιον τῶν μαθητῶν αὐτοῦ ἃ οὐκ ἔστιν γεγραμμένα ἐν τῷ βιβλίῳ τούτῳ',
   'Polla men oun kai alla sēmeia epoiēsen ho Iēsous enōpion tōn mathētōn autou ha ouk estin gegrammena en tō bibliō toutō',
   '''Many other signs truly did Jesus... which are not written in this book'' (oun kai alla sēmeia epoiēsen... ha ouk estin gegrammena en tō bibliō toutō — and many other signs... which are not written in this book). The Gospel is a selection — a highly intentional, theologically purposeful selection — from a much larger body of events. John acknowledges the selection explicitly. 21:25 will expand this: ''the world itself could not contain the books that should be written.''',
   NULL),
  (31, 'But these are written, that ye might believe that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of God; and that believing ye might have life through his name.',
   'ταῦτα δὲ γέγραπται ἵνα πιστεύσητε ὅτι Ἰησοῦς ἐστιν ὁ χριστὸς ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ θεοῦ καὶ ἵνα πιστεύοντες ζωὴν ἔχητε ἐν τῷ ὀνόματι αὐτοῦ',
   'tauta de gegraptai hina pisteusēte hoti Iēsous estin ho christos ho huios tou theou kai hina pisteuontes zōēn echēte en tō onomati autou',
   '''These are written, that ye might believe'' (gegraptai hina pisteusēte — have been written so that you may believe). The stated purpose of the Gospel of John: to produce faith. ''That Jesus is the Christ, the Son of God'' — the dual title: Christos (the anointed one, the Messiah — the human, royal title) and the Son of God (the divine title). The Gospel began by affirming both (1:1-18); it ends by restating them as the object of faith. ''That believing ye might have life through his name'' (hina pisteusēte zōēn echēte en tō onomati autou — so that believing you may have life in his name). Life through his name: the name represents the person; to have life in his name is to have life through union with him. This is the Gospel in one verse: believe → life. ''Life'' (zōēn echēte — may have/possess life; the same eternal life promised in 3:16; 6:40; 10:10; 17:3).',
   NULL)
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 20;
